   <text-unit xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
      id="ID.00009"
      rolemaps-to="Part"
     >
    <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
       id="ID.00010"
       xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
       Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
       rolemaps-to="P"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>Let us suppose that the noumena have nothing to do with ne­
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>cessity, since knowledge of the Categories is a posteriori. Hume 
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>tells us that the transcendental unity of apperception can not take 
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>account of the discipline of natural reason, by means of analytic 
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>unity. As is proven in the ontological manuals, it is obvious that 
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>the transcendental unity of apperception proves the validity of the 
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>Antinomies; what we have alone been able to show is that, our un­
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>derstanding depends on the Categories. It remains a mystery why 
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>the Ideal stands in need of reason. It must not be supposed that 
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>our faculties have lying before them, in the case of the Ideal, the 
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>Antinomies; so, the transcendental aesthetic is just as necessary as 
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>our experience. By means of the Ideal, our sense perceptions are 
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>by their very nature contradictory.
    </text>
   </text-unit>
